posts.cooked:
I’ve been messing around with pocketed aluminum in CAD a bit recently and was wondering if anyone had any knowledge/insight on how to balance weight reduction with strength? Our team hasn’t done much with pocketed aluminum in the past so any insight on how to determine how much material to leave on, where there should be ribs and their thickness, how to determine loads, etc. when using pocketed aluminum in different situations would be much appreciated!

posts.name: Will C
posts.cooked: We have a Shapeoko CNC with a 80mm 220V VFD Spindle we’re using. The hex bore will likely be cut a little undersize and finished with a 1/2" hex reamer. All the pocketing was done using an Onshape feature script using 0.3" ribs and a 1/4" endmill. We’ve already made these plates the same way out of 1/4" Lexan (with 0.5" ribs), but I’m looking for ways to switch to 3/16" Aluminum and remove more material while balancing weight and strength. I’d also like to start utilizing similar techniques in the future for certain use cases, but our team has never tried it before

posts.name: Kevin Clark
posts.cooked:
I had the same question because in general, fabrication method should inform design. There are a few very small pockets here. Do you have a tool that will fit? Additionally, entering stock with a mill tends to be slower than removing material once you’re through. That means fewer large pockets will be faster than more small pockets even if they cover the same weight savings and have (hand wave) similar structural properties. And while you can speed things up with a roughing end mill, that requires being able to fit it into the pocket (and still may need follow up with a smaller tool to compensate for a larger radius).

Edit: I see you’re running a Shapeoko. I would definitely talk to your fabrication team about how they plan to handle this. Small decisions at the design phase can make significant differences in fabrication time.

posts.name: Ardiano Works
posts.cooked:
I’d use 1/4" Dia cutter if you can. Adapt your corner radius to this size cutter. This is cheap and everywhere, get a single flute up cut cutter too. This would leave clean edge on the bottom then run a chamfering tool on the top . This way you have less effort deburring.

Those smaller cut outs, are they necessary? do you really need to remove that tiny weight? simplify your parts make it easier to cut. bigger slots.

Think about how you want to hold this. What type of clamp are u going to use. Make sure the clamps are not in the way.  Are you going to do this in Router or VMC?

posts.name: Kevin Clark
posts.cooked: We’ve moved to roughing pockets with a 10mm end mill and then doing rest machining and contouring with a 6mm (both from WCP and reasonably cheap) and it’s radically increased our fabrication speed. We rough .150” down and .100 step over vs .50 and .50 with the 6mm (and previously our 1/4”). It took down a 6.5 hour belly pan we cut for 1458 out of 1/8” 6061 down to under 2 hours and I think we can go faster after some tuning.

First, cut unnecessary dimensions from the outside. Unnessesary material being saved on the outside will save weight faster than pocketing the middle and comes with less of a strength penalty, and will make the overall pocketing more efficient. This plate isn’t super problematic in that regard, but its important to always do this first.

Next, connect all points of interest and required surfaces for contact with stuff, but no more. If a strut is not carrying any load, it has no reason to exist and just adds weight. The circle around the motor cutout isn’t carrying load, so no reason to put structure there. Same for the circle on the bottom left. The right half of your plate on top is fine, but the left half has a lot of struts that are doing nothing. I would try something like this.

image 920×646 81.9 KB

image 920×646 81.9 KB

image 920×646 81.9 KB

If you need more bending resistance, use a beam to reinforce the plate instead of more structs. Plates are bad in bending are more plates won’t help much, but adding a beam along the length of the plate will help a lot.

Internal radii should be fairly large as small radii are stress risers which significantly increase stress. This also allows for larger radii endmills to be used which can remove material faster. Micropockets should generally be avoided as they increase machine time and add stress risers while providing minimal weight gain.

posts.cooked: Depends on how much load I am expecting and the plate thickness. If its like .25 plate, fairly thin, but for like 1/8th plate, thicker. When you pocket, you turn a plate into a bunch of beams, and you want each individual beam to be strong enough.
